result.execSummary:
The defendant Tamara Shae Predzik was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Tamara Shae Predzik in court. Defnedant is in custody. Prosecuting Assistant District Attorney (ADA) Cass W Cousins appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

9:22 AM Court calls case.
Court states appearances.

Defendant is here without a lawyer.

Defendant was here in June, requesting a lawyer.
Defendant still has to get a lawyer, was told one was going to be appointed and was to get a new court date.
Defendant is a Marathon County inmate, being housed in Lincoln County, probation is revoked in Marathon County.  

Defendant still wishes to be represented by a lawyer.
There is no one from the public defender's office out in the hallway at this time.

Defendant indicates that she wishes now to go forward without a lawyer.
Court questions Defendant as to right to counsel. Department of Corrections is recommending a prison sentence. 
Court questions Defendant as to her current jail sentences and further inquires.

Atty Cousins has not had contact with any attorney in this case. 
Revocation summary was forwarded to the public defender's office.

9:28 AM Public Defender's Office is called at this time.
Court explains as to status of this case. 
Twice now Defendant has appeared without counsel.

Public Defender's Office has her not eligible, owns a house outright. 
Defendant indicates that her husband owes the house, is separated from her husband.
Defendant never notified the office of this. 
No one lives in the house, is in Wausau. Her husband is in prison for almost 2 years, separated for four years.
Defendant has two children. 
Court continues questioning Defendant.

Ms. Sommerfeld (sp) replies as to how Defendant can contact the office.
Atty Roberts-Turner or Atty Drengler will come over to speak with Defendant, not necessarily represent Defendant, but mostly to just talk.
Defendant will be sitting in Branch 3.  

Defendant will be kept in Court for a few minutes.

9:34 AM Court is in recess.

9:54 AM Court re-calls case.
Atty Renc is speaking with the DA's office at this time.
Case will be passed over at this time.

10:02 AM Court re-calls case.
Court thanks Atty Renc for coming over.
Atty Renc states that Defendant does not qualify for a public defender but is willing to make a special appearance, spoke with the State and has a joint recommendation.

Atty Renc has reviewed the revocation packet.
Atty Cousins makes recommendation.

Atty Renc addresses the Court.

Court has a number of factors to consider to determine sentencing.

BY THE COURT:
Determinate prison sentence for 3 years
Initial confinement for 1 year
Extended supervision for 2 years
146 days credit
Concurrent to all other sentences Defendant is currently serving
Eligible for earned release and challenge incarceration
Conditions:
Same as orginially imposed as a condition of probation
Pay court costs, to be taken out of prison account at a reasonable rate determined by Department of Corrections

Written explanation of determinate sentence is addressed. Defendant will get a copy of this.
